The anatomical snuffbox is a triangular depression located on the radial aspect of the dorsum of the hand between the tendons of the extensor pollicis longus and extensor pollicis brevis. The radial artery is the primary artery that supplies the region, making it the most likely artery responsible for the excessive bleeding.

The ulnar artery runs along the ulnar side of the wrist and the princeps pollicis artery supplies the thumb, while the brachial artery is located in the upper arm and would not be responsible for bleeding from the hand.

The princeps pollicis artery branches off the radial artery, so damage to this branch may contribute to bleeding, but damage to the main radial artery is more significant. The brachial artery is located in the upper arm and is not involved in the blood supply to the hand.
